THE boss of a Durban taxi association has been arrested in Verulam, north of Durban, for being in possession of illegal firearms.The arms included two R5 and one AK47 assault rifles.Cops suspect that the firearms were used in taxi-related violence which has claimed many lives in the province.The suspect (43) was arrested on Tuesday night at a house in High Street in the area by members of the National Mobile Train Unit.Police said the unit was following up on information about suspected stolen vehicles and illegal firearms which had led them to the suspect.Provincial police spokeswoman Colonel Thembeka Mbhele said a white Suzuki vehicle recovered at the premises was found to have been hijacked in Mthunzini in May.&ldquo;When the members asked for the car keys the suspect could not provide them and the unit members had to break a side window in order to search it.&ldquo;Inside the vehicle, three rifles with four fully loaded magazines were recovered,&rdquo; said Mbhele.She said another vehicle, a grey BMW, was also found to have been hijacked at Greenwood Park this month. &ldquo;The 43-year-old suspect was arrested and charged with possession of unlicensed firearms and ammunition and possession of suspected stolen vehicles.&ldquo;He will appear in the Verulam Magistrates Court soon,&rdquo; Mbhele said.The acting KZN provincial police commissioner, Major-General Bheki Langa, applauded the members for recovering the unlicensed firearms and ammunition. &ldquo;The recovered firearms will be taken to ballistics to check if they were used in any commission of a crime in the country and in taxi-related crimes,&rdquo; said Langa.